2025-09-04T10:44:54.064029Z assistant

Exactly EBS = Elastic Block Store.

Thats the persistent storage that pairs with your EC2 instance. Think of it like:

  • EC2 = the computer (CPU + RAM, but no permanent disk)
  • EBS = the hard drive (keeps your files safe even when EC2 is stopped/restarted)

Without EBS, any data written to EC2s root volume disappears when the instance is terminated. With EBS attached, your Annals archive, exports, Codex patches, and ingestion pipeline can all survive across reboots and instance cycles.

Quick AWS CLI Workflow

Heres how youd do it step by step:

1. Create a Volume

aws ec2 create-volume \
  --availability-zone us-east-1a \
  --size 20 \
  --volume-type gp3 \
  --tag-specifications 'ResourceType=volume,Tags=[{Key=Name,Value=CelticKeyAnnals}]'
  • --size 20 = 20 GB (adjust as needed)
  • gp3 = general-purpose SSD, cheapest option thats solid for logs
  • --availability-zone must match your EC2 instances AZ

2. Attach Volume to Your EC2

aws ec2 attach-volume \
  --volume-id vol-xxxxxxxx \
  --instance-id i-xxxxxxxx \
  --device /dev/xvdf

3. Format & Mount It (on EC2 itself)

SSH into your instance:

ssh -i your-key.pem ubuntu@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>

Then:

# Format as ext4
sudo mkfs -t ext4 /dev/xvdf

# Make a mount point
sudo mkdir /mnt/celtic-key

# Mount it
sudo mount /dev/xvdf /mnt/celtic-key

4. Persist Mount Across Reboots

Get UUID:

sudo blkid /dev/xvdf

Edit fstab:

sudo nano /etc/fstab

Add:

UUID=<copied-uuid>  /mnt/celtic-key  ext4  defaults,nofail  0  2

From then on:

  • /mnt/celtic-key = your Annals archive root
  • Safe even if EC2 restarts
  • Expandable later if your archive grows

Thats the AWS side. The Annals side (Markdown + Codex patches) just needs a consistent template, and youll have a living, queryable memory system that persists no matter what.
